# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fuse-electrical
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In automobiles, a **42-volt electrical system** was an electrical power standard proposed in the late 1990s.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] It was intended to facilitate increasingly-powerful electrically-driven accessories in automobiles, and lighter wiring harnesses.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Electric motors were proposed to be used for power steering or other systems, providing more compact installations and eliminating the weight of drive belts or large wires for high-current loads.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The proposed new standard was exactly triple the voltage of existing "12-volt" systems.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The higher voltage was selected to provide greater power capacity for wiring and devices on one hand, and to stay under the 50-volt limit used as a guideline for electric shock hazard.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The European auto manufacturer Daimler-Benz proposed a *42V* brand name for the conversion.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Although many manufacturers were predicting a switch to 36-volt (lithium-ion battery) / 42-volt (charging voltage) electrical systems, the "42V" changeover did not occur by early in the 21st century, and plans were mostly abandoned by 2009.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators largely eliminated the 2000s cross-industry push for raising the main automotive voltages.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Applications that once were thought to require higher voltages, such as electrical power steering, were subsequently achieved with 12-volt systems.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In the late 2000s, 42-volt electrical components were used in only a few automotive applications, since incandescent light bulbs work well at 12 volts and switching of a 42-volt circuit is more difficult.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In the 2010s, 48-volt electrical systems became popular.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The SAE discussed an increased automobile standard voltage as early as 1988.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] From the outset, the participants in this workshop included suppliers as well as the automobile companies Daimler-Benz, Ford and General Motors.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In September 1995, various electrical systems architectures were compared at MIT using the tool "MAESTrO", and in December 1995, in the "Conclusions" of this study, a future voltage level of approximately 40 V was defined.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In early 1996, the "Consortium on Advanced Automotive Electrical and Electronic Systems" was set up.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] At the ensuing workshop in March 1996, the future nominal voltage of 42 V was confirmed.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In August 1996, IEEE Spectrum published the paper "Automotive electrical systems circa 2005".
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] On the occasion of the October 1996 Convergence in Detroit, Professor John G.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Kassakian (MIT) gave a talk entitled "The Future of Automotive Electrical Systems" as part of the "IEEE Workshop on Automotive Power- Electronics".
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] On March 24, 1997, Daimler-Benz presented the MIT with a "Draft Specification of a Dual Voltage Vehicle Electrical Power System 42V/14V".
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] At the same time as the activities in the USA, in 1994, again at the initiative of Daimler-Benz, the former SICAN GmbH held its first "*Forum Bordnetz*" (Vehicle Electrical System Forum) in Hanover for German automobile companies.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Here too, suppliers were invited to participate at a very early stage, together with all European vehicle manufacturers.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] On September 13, 1996, at the 7th International Technical Meeting for Vehicle Electronics in Baden-Baden, considerable interest was raised by the paper "*Neue Bordnetz- Architektur und Konsequenzen*" (New Automotive Electrical System Architecture and Consequences), presented by Dr.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] On March 6, 1997, BMW presented the "*Spezifikationsentwurf für das Zwei-Spannungsbordnetz 42V/14V*" (Draft Specification of a Dual Voltage Vehicle Electrical Power System 42V/14V) in Hanover.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The work at SICAN GmbH was given decisive impetus by the cooperation between BMW and Daimler-Benz, as witnessed in their joint definition of the European "Load List 2005" and the jointly authored "Draft Specification of a Dual Voltage Vehicle Electrical Power System 42V/14V".
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Volvo has used 42 V for some of its mild hybrids.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The increased adoption of hybrid vehicle technologies in the 2010s led to 48-volt systems being deployed in mild hybrid vehicles, which add electric boost to the typical internal combustion engine (ICE) propulsion, and facilitates some regeneration during braking for fuel savings.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In 2011, several German car makers agreed on a 48 V on-board electric power supply network on top of the current 12 V network and introduced the "Combo plug", a common power plug for DC charging electric vehicles.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] As of 2018, this 48-volt electrical system had been applied in production vehicles such as Porsche and Bentley SUVs, while Volvo and Audi planned to use the 48-volt standard in 2019 vehicles.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In March 2023, Tesla Inc. began production of the Cybertruck with a 48-volt architecture, the first production vehicle to use 48 volts as the system voltage for the entire low-voltage system.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] They have indicated that their next-generation vehicle will also be utilizing a 48 V low-voltage electrical system as well.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Six-cell lead–acid batteries produce around 12.6 volts while discharging, and their corresponding automotive alternators are designed to produce 13.5 to 14.5 volts during charging.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] 42 volts is an approximation of the output of the new standard's charging system.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The present nominally 12 V automotive electrical system usually operates around 13.8 volts, so 14 V is descriptive.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Literature on 42-volt electrical systems often refers to systems powered with a 6-cell lead-acid battery as nominally 14 volts.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Depending on operating conditions, the vehicle electrical system voltage today can vary between 6.5 and 16 V, with a varying degree of ripple superimposed on this value.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The finding of this study was that the highest possible direct voltage was the best alternative.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The limiting factor for direct voltages is a shock-hazard protection limit of 60 V, which must not be exceeded even during voltage fluctuations caused by extreme conditions.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] This limit eliminates the option of an automotive electrical system with a nominal battery voltage of 48 V, because at low temperatures the charging voltage of the battery can attain 60 V.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Also, the price, weight and volume of batteries are influenced by the number of cells, which must therefore be kept to a minimum.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] New battery technologies for automotive applications would not have been available at affordable costs for the 42 V/14 V PowerNet.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Lead-acid batteries are low-priced and have a very "compliant" charging/discharging characteristic.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Therefore, lead-acid batteries would have been used optimised for energy and service life at the lower voltage and optimised for power at the higher voltage.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Another important criterion for a new architecture was that it should allow gradual conversion of loads to the higher voltage system as required.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In a 42 V/14 V system, the 14 V branch should have been freed of higher-power loads and should operate within much narrower limits.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Power electronics is becoming increasingly important in the automotive sphere and will be a decisive factor in the price of future vehicles.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] This criterion was therefore especially important when selecting the most suitable higher voltage level.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Despite the considerable upward trend of power electronics in automotive applications, its share of the market will decline, because growth rates in other market segments are even higher.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] For that reason alone, a specific manufacturing technology for automotive use is inconceivable.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] In intensive discussions with the major semiconductor manufacturers, a voltage of approximately 40 V was found to be advantageous.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] Other arguments for a higher voltage included the reduction of weight in the wiring system, improved stability, and reduced voltage drop.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] With three times the voltage, thick conductors can be reduced to a third of the cross-section, and at the same time the relative voltage drop can also be reduced to a third.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] For the same cross-section, the relative voltage drop is now no more than one ninth.
[src:fuse-electrical/42-volt-electrical-system] The voltage level resulting from these arguments was so close to three times the present voltage that 42 V became the automatic choice for the second voltage level.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:fuse-electrical/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] An **acorn tube**, or **acorn valve**, is any member of a family of VHF/UHF vacuum tubes starting just before World War II.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] They were named after their resemblance to the acorn, specifically due to the glass cap at one end of the tube that looked similar to the cap on an acorn.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] The acorn tubes found widespread use in radios and radar systems.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] High-frequency performance is limited by (1) parasitic lead inductance and capacitance and skin effect, and (2) electron transit time (the time required to travel from cathode to anode).
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] Transit time effects are complicated, but one simple effect is the phase margin; another one is input conductance, also known as grid loading.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] At extremely high frequencies, electrons arriving at the grid may become out of phase with those departing towards the anode.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] This imbalance of charge causes the grid to exhibit a reactance that is much less than its low-frequency "open circuit" characteristic.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] Acorn- as well as Lighthouse tubes and Nuvistors attempt to minimize this effect by arranging cathode, grid(s) and anode as closely spaced together as possible.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] The original range included about half a dozen tubes, designed to work in the VHF range.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] The 954 and 956 types are sharp and remote cut-off pentodes, respectively, all with indirect 6.3 V, 150 mA heaters.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] Types 957, 958 and 959 are for portable equipment and have 1.25 V NiCd battery heaters.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] The 957 is a medium-μ signal triode, the 958 is a transmitting triode with dual, paralleled filaments for increased emission, and the 959 is a sharp cut-off pentode like the 954.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] The 957 and 959 draw 50 mA heater current, the 958 twice as much.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] In 1942, the 958A with tightened emission specifications was introduced after it turned out that 958s with excessively high emission kept working after the filament power was turned off, the filament still sufficiently heating on the anode current alone.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] After the introduction of the miniature 7-pin base, the 954, 955 and 956 were made available with this base as 9001, 9002 and 9003.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] Larger, higher-power types such as the 316A, 368A, 388A, and 703A triodes and the 713A and 717A pentodes were referred to as *Doorknob* tubes.
[src:fuse-electrical/acorn-tube] The introduction of the EF50 was the first serious competition for the acorn design, and replaced the acorns in many roles, especially post-war when millions of surplus EF50s were dumped on the market.
[src:fuse-electrical/additron-tube] The **Additron** was an electron tube designed by Dr.
[src:fuse-electrical/additron-tube] Josef Kates, circa 1950, to replace the several individual electron tubes and support components required to perform the function of a single bit digital full adder.
[src:fuse-electrical/additron-tube] The Additron neither went into production at the Canadian Rogers Vacuum Tube Company, where the prototypes were built, nor was it used in the UTEC machine.
[src:fuse-electrical/additron-tube] It did make a widely publicized appearance at the 1950 Canadian National Exhibition operating an electronic game of Tic-Tac-Toe, dubbed *Bertie the Brain*, to show the marvels of electronic computing.
[src:fuse-electrical/additron-tube] The tube was registered with the Radio Television Manufacturing Association on 20 March 1951 as type 6047.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The germanium **alloy-junction transistor**, or **alloy transistor**, was an early type of bipolar junction transistor, developed at General Electric and RCA in 1951 as an improvement over the earlier grown-junction transistor.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The usual construction of an alloy-junction transistor is a germanium crystal forming the base, with emitter and collector alloy beads fused on opposite sides.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] Indium and antimony were commonly used to form the alloy junctions on a bar of N-type germanium.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The collector junction pellet would be about 50 mils (thousandths of an inch) in diameter, and the emitter pellet about 20 mils.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The base region would be on the order of 1 mil (0.001 inches, 25 μm) thick.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] There were several types of improved alloy-junction transistors developed over the years that they were manufactured.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] All types of alloy-junction transistors became obsolete in the early 1960s, with the introduction of the planar transistor which could be mass-produced easily while alloy-junction transistors had to be made individually.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The first germanium planar transistors had much worse characteristics than alloy-junction germanium transistors of the period, but they cost much less, and the characteristics of planar transistors improved very rapidly, quickly exceeding those of all earlier germanium transistors.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy transistor** (**MAT**) was developed by Philco as an improved type of alloy-junction transistor, it offered much higher speed.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] It is constructed of a semiconductor crystal forming the base, into which a pair of wells are etched (similar to Philco's earlier surface-barrier transistor) on opposite sides then fusing emitter and collector alloy beads into the wells.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy diffused transistor** (**MADT**), or **micro-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philco as an improved type of micro-alloy transistor; it offered even higher speed.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] It is a type of diffused-base transistor.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] Before using electrochemical techniques and etching depression wells into the base semiconductor crystal material, a heated diffused phosphorus gaseous layer is created over the entire intrinsic semiconductor base crystal, creating a N-type graded base semiconductor material.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The emitter well is etched very shallow into this diffused base layer.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] For high-speed operation, the collector well is etched all the way through the diffused base layer and through most of the intrinsic base semiconductor region, forming an extremely thin base region.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] A doping-engineered electric field was created in the diffused base layer to reduce the charge carrier base transit time (similar to the drift-field transistor).
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The **post-alloy diffused transistor** (**PADT**), or **post-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philips (but GE and RCA filed for patent and Jacques Pankove of RCA received patent for it) as an improvement to the germanium alloy-junction transistor, it offered even higher speed.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The Philco micro-alloy diffused transistor had a mechanical weakness that ultimately limited their speed; the thin diffused base layer would break if made too thin, but to get high speed it needed to be as thin as possible.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] Also it was very hard to control alloying on both sides of such a thin layer.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The post-alloy diffused transistor solved this problem by making the bulk semiconductor crystal the collector (instead of the base), which could be as thick as necessary for mechanical strength.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The diffused base layer was created on top of this.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] Then two alloy beads, one P-type and one N-type were fused on top of the diffused base layer.
[src:fuse-electrical/alloy-junction-transistor] The bead having the same type as the base dopant then became part of the base and the bead having the opposite type from the base dopant became the emitter.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] The ampacity of a conductor depends on its ability to dissipate heat without damage to the conductor or its insulation.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] This is a function of the insulation temperature rating, the electrical resistance of the conductor material, the ambient temperature, and the ability of the insulated conductor to dissipate heat to the surroundings.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] All common electrical conductors have some resistance to the flow of electricity.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Electric current flowing through conductors heats them.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] If heat is produced at a sufficient rate, the conductor temperature rises and the insulation can be damaged or ultimately the conductor itself can sag or melt.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] The ampacity rating for a conductor is based on the conductor diameter, material used (copper or aluminum), the rated maximum application temperature, and the installation conditions.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Installation regulations describe the required factors to be applied for any particular installation.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Conductors installed so that air can freely move over them can be rated to carry more current than conductors run inside a conduit or buried underground.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] High ambient temperature may reduce the current rating of a conductor.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Cables run in wet or oily locations may carry a lower temperature rating than in a dry installation.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] A lower rating will apply if multiple conductors are in proximity, since each contributes heat to the others and diminishes the amount of external cooling of the conductors.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Depending on the type of insulating material, common maximum allowable temperatures at the surface of the conductor are 60, 75, and 90 °C, often with an ambient air temperature of 30 °C.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] In the United States, 105 °C is allowed with ambient of 40 °C, for larger power cables, especially those operating at more than 2 kV.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Likewise, specific insulations are rated 150, 200, or 250 °C.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] The allowed current in a conductor generally needs to be decreased (derated) when conductors are in a grouping or cable, enclosed in conduit, or an enclosure restricting heat dissipation.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] A single insulated conductor in free air has 70 A rating.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Ampacity rating is normally for continuous current, and short periods of overcurrent occur without harm in most cabling systems.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Electrical code rules will give ratings for wiring where short-term loads are present, for example, in a hoisting motor.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] For systems such as underground power transmission cables, evaluation of the short-term over-load capacity of the cable system requires a detailed analysis of the cable's thermal environment and an evaluation of the commercial value of the lost service life due to excess temperature rise.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampacity] Design of an electrical system will normally include consideration of the current-carrying capacity of all conductors of the system.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The **ampere** (/ˈæmpɛər/ ⓘ *AM-pair*, US: /ˈæmpɪər/ ⓘ *AM-peer*; symbol: **A**), often shortened to **amp**, is the unit of electric current in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] One ampere is equal to 1 coulomb (C) moving past a point per second.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] It is named after French mathematician and physicist André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), considered the father of electromagnetism along with Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] Prior to the redefinition, the ampere was defined as the current passing through two parallel wires 1 metre apart that produces a magnetic force of 2×10−7 newtons per metre.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The earlier CGS system has two units of current, one structured similarly to the SI's and the other using Coulomb's law as a fundamental relationship, with the CGS unit of charge defined by measuring the force between two charged metal plates.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The CGS unit of current is then defined as one unit of charge per second.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The ampere is named for French physicist and mathematician André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), who studied electromagnetism and laid the foundation of electrodynamics.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] In recognition of Ampère's contributions to the creation of modern electrical science, an international convention, signed at the 1881 International Exposition of Electricity, established the ampere as a standard unit of electrical measurement for electric current.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The ampere was originally defined as one tenth of the unit of electric current in the centimetre–gram–second system of units.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] That unit, now known as the abampere, was defined as the amount of current that generates a force of two dynes per centimetre of length between two wires one centimetre apart.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The size of the unit was chosen so that the units derived from it in the MKSA system would be conveniently sized.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The "international ampere" was an early realisation of the ampere, defined as the current that would deposit 0.001118 grams of silver per second from a silver nitrate solution.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] Later, more accurate measurements revealed that this current is 0.99985 A.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] Since power is defined as the product of current and voltage, the ampere can alternatively be expressed in terms of the other units using the relationship *I* = *P*/*V*, and thus 1 A = 1 W/V.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] Current can be measured by a multimeter, a device that can measure electrical voltage, current, and resistance.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] Ampère's force law states that there is an attractive or repulsive force between two parallel wires carrying an electric current.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] This force was used in the formal definition of the ampere, giving the vacuum magnetic permeability (magnetic constant, *μ*0) a value of exactly 4π × 10−7 henries per metre (H/m, equivalent to N/A2).
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, was then defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] In general, charge Q was determined by steady current I flowing for a time t as *Q* = *It*.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] Techniques to establish the realisation of an ampere had a relative uncertainty of approximately a few parts in 107, and involved realisations of the watt, the ohm and the volt.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, "is the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] The relation of the ampere (A = C/s) to the coulomb (C) is the same as that of the watt (W = J/s) to the joule (J).
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] These SI derived units can either be given special names e.g. watt, volt, lux, etc. or defined in terms of others, e.g. metre per second.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] There are also some SI units that are frequently used in the context of electrical engineering and electrical appliances, but are defined independently of the ampere, notably the hertz, joule, watt, candela, lumen, and lux.
[src:fuse-electrical/ampere] Like other SI units, the ampere can be modified by adding a prefix that multiplies it by a power of 10.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In electronics and electrical engineering, a **fuse** is an electrical safety device that operates to provide overcurrent protection of an electrical circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Its essential component is a metal wire or strip that melts when too much current flows through it, thereby stopping or interrupting the current.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] It is a sacrificial device; once a fuse has operated, it is an open circuit, and must be replaced or rewired, depending on its type.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses have been used as essential safety devices from the early days of electrical engineering.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Today there are thousands of different fuse designs which have specific current and voltage ratings, breaking capacity, and response times, depending on the application.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The time and current operating characteristics of fuses are chosen to provide adequate protection without needless interruption.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Wiring regulations usually define a maximum fuse current rating for particular circuits.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A fuse can be used to mitigate short circuits, overloading, mismatched loads, or device failure.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] When a damaged live wire makes contact with a metal case that is connected to ground, a short circuit will form and the fuse will melt.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A fuse is an automatic means of removing power from a faulty system, often abbreviated to ADS (automatic disconnection of supply).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Circuit breakers have replaced fuses in many contexts, but have significantly different characteristics, and fuses are still used when space, resiliency or cost are significant factors.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Louis Clément François Breguet recommended the use of reduced-section conductors to protect telegraph stations from lightning strikes; by melting, the smaller wires would protect apparatus and wiring inside the building.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A variety of wire or foil fusible elements were in use to protect telegraph cables and lighting installations as early as 1864.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A fuse was patented by Thomas Edison in 1890 as part of his electric distribution system.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A fuse consists of a metal strip or wire fuse element, of small cross-section compared to the circuit conductors, mounted between a pair of electrical terminals, and (usually) enclosed by a non-combustible housing.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The fuse is arranged in series to carry all the charge passing through the protected circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The resistance of the element generates heat due to the current flow.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The size and construction of the element is (empirically) determined so that the heat produced for a normal current does not cause the element to attain a high temperature.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] If too high of a current flows, the element rises to a higher temperature and either directly melts, or else melts a soldered joint within the fuse, opening the circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The fuse element is made of zinc, copper, silver, aluminium, or alloys among these or other various metals to provide stable and predictable characteristics.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The fuse ideally would carry its rated current indefinitely, and melt quickly on a small excess.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The element must not be damaged by minor harmless surges of current, and must not oxidize or change its behavior after possibly years of service.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The fuse elements may be shaped to increase heating effect.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In large fuses, current may be divided between multiple strips of metal.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A dual-element fuse may contain a metal strip that melts instantly on a short circuit, and also contain a low-melting solder joint that responds to long-term overload of low values compared to a short circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuse elements may be supported by steel or nichrome wires, so that no strain is placed on the element, but a spring may be included to increase the speed of parting of the element fragments.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The fuse element may be surrounded by air, or by materials intended to speed the quenching of the arc.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Silica sand or non-conducting liquids may be used.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A maximum current that the fuse can continuously conduct without interrupting the circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The speed at which a fuse blows depends on how much current flows through it and the material of which the fuse is made.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Manufacturers can provide a plot of current vs time, often plotted on logarithmic scales, to characterize the device and to allow comparison with the characteristics of protective devices upstream and downstream of the fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The operating time is not a fixed interval but decreases as the current increases.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses are designed to have particular characteristics of operating time compared to current.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A standard fuse may require twice its rated current to open in one second, a fast-blow fuse may require twice its rated current to blow in 0.1 seconds, and a slow-blow fuse may require twice its rated current for tens of seconds to blow.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuse selection depends on the load's characteristics.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Semiconductor devices may use a fast or *ultrafast* fuse as semiconductor devices heat rapidly when excess current flows.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The fastest blowing fuses are designed for the most sensitive electrical equipment, where even a short exposure to an overload current could be damaging.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Normal fast-blow fuses are the most general purpose fuses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A *time-delay fuse* (also known as an *anti-surge* or *slow-blow* fuse) is designed to allow a current which is above the rated value of the fuse to flow for a short period of time without the fuse blowing.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] These types of fuse are used on equipment such as motors, which can draw larger than normal currents for up to several seconds while coming up to speed.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The I2t rating is related to the amount of energy let through by the fuse element when it clears the electrical fault.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This term is normally used in short circuit conditions and the values are used to perform co-ordination studies in electrical networks.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] I2t parameters are provided by charts in manufacturer data sheets for each fuse family.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] For coordination of fuse operation with upstream or downstream devices, both melting I2t and clearing I2t are specified.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The melting I2t is proportional to the amount of energy required to begin melting the fuse element.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The clearing I2t is proportional to the total energy let through by the fuse when clearing a fault.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The energy is mainly dependent on current and time for fuses as well as the available fault level and system voltage.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Since the I2t rating of the fuse is proportional to the energy it lets through, it is a measure of the thermal damage from the heat and magnetic forces that will be produced by a fault end.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The breaking capacity is the maximum current that can safely be interrupted by the fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This should be higher than the prospective short-circuit current.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Miniature fuses may have an interrupting rating only 10 times their rated current.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses for small, low-voltage, usually residential, wiring systems are commonly rated, in North American practice, to interrupt 10,000 amperes.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses for commercial or industrial power systems must have higher interrupting ratings, with some low-voltage current-limiting high interrupting fuses rated for 300,000 amperes.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses for high-voltage equipment, up to 115,000 volts, are rated by the total apparent power (megavolt-amperes, MVA) of the fault level on the circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some fuses are designated high rupture capacity (HRC) or high breaking capacity (HBC) and are usually filled with sand or a similar material.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Low-voltage high rupture capacity (HRC) fuses are used in the area of main distribution boards in low-voltage networks where there is a high prospective short circuit current.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] They are generally larger than screw-type fuses, and have ferrule cap or blade contacts.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] High rupture capacity fuses may be rated to interrupt current of 120 kA.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] HRC fuses are widely used in industrial installations and are also used in the public power grid, e.g. in transformer stations, main distribution boards, or in building junction boxes and as meter fuses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In some countries, because of the high fault current available where these fuses are used, local regulations may permit only trained personnel to change these fuses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some varieties of HRC fuse include special handling features.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The voltage rating of the fuse must be equal to or, greater than, what would become the open-circuit voltage.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] For example, a glass tube fuse rated at 32 volts would not reliably interrupt current from a voltage source of 120 or 230 V.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] If a 32 V fuse attempts to interrupt the 120 or 230 V source, an arc may result.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Plasma inside the glass tube may continue to conduct current until the current diminishes to the point where the plasma becomes a non-conducting gas.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Rated voltage should be higher than the maximum voltage source it would have to disconnect.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Connecting fuses in series does not increase the rated voltage of the combination, nor of any one fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Medium-voltage fuses rated for a few thousand volts are never used on low voltage circuits, because of their cost and because they cannot properly clear the circuit when operating at very low voltages.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The manufacturer may specify the voltage drop across the fuse at rated current.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] There is a direct relationship between a fuse's cold resistance and its voltage drop value.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Once current is applied, resistance and voltage drop of a fuse will constantly grow with the rise of its operating temperature until the fuse finally reaches thermal equilibrium.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The voltage drop should be taken into account, particularly when using a fuse in low-voltage applications.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Voltage drop often is not significant in more traditional wire type fuses, but can be significant in other technologies such as resettable (PPTC) type fuses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Ambient temperature will change a fuse's operational parameters.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A fuse rated for 1 A at 25 °C may conduct up to 10% or 20% more current at −40 °C and may open at 80% of its rated value at 100 °C.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Operating values will vary with each fuse family and are provided in manufacturer data sheets.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Most fuses are marked on the body or end caps with markings that indicate their ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Surface-mount technology "chip type" fuses feature few or no markings, making identification very difficult.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Similar appearing fuses may have significantly different properties, identified by their markings.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses come in a vast array of sizes and styles to serve in many applications, manufactured in standardised package layouts to make them easily interchangeable.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuse bodies may be made of ceramic, glass, plastic, fiberglass, molded mica laminates, or molded compressed fibre depending on application and voltage class.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Cartridge (ferrule) fuses have a cylindrical body terminated with metal end caps.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some cartridge fuses are manufactured with end caps of different sizes to prevent accidental insertion of the wrong fuse rating in a holder, giving them a bottle shape.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses for low voltage power circuits may have bolted blade or tag terminals which are secured by screws to a fuseholder.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some blade-type terminals are held by spring clips.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Blade type fuses often require the use of a special purpose extractor tool to remove them from the fuse holder.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Renewable fuses have replaceable fuse elements, allowing the fuse body and terminals to be reused if not damaged after a fuse operation.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses designed for soldering to a printed circuit board have radial or axial wire leads.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Surface mount fuses have solder pads instead of leads.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] High-voltage fuses of the expulsion type have fiber or glass-reinforced plastic tubes and an open end, and can have the fuse element replaced.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] These are still used in consumer units in some parts of the world, but are becoming less common.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] While glass fuses have the advantage of a fuse element visible for inspection purposes, they have a low breaking capacity (interrupting rating), which generally restricts them to applications of 15 A or less at 250 VAC.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Ceramic fuses have the advantage of a higher breaking capacity, facilitating their use in circuits with higher current and voltage.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Filling a fuse body with sand provides additional cooling of the arc and increases the breaking capacity of the fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Medium-voltage fuses may have liquid-filled envelopes to assist in the extinguishing of the arc.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some types of distribution switchgear use fuse links immersed in the oil that fills the equipment.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuse packages may include a rejection feature such as a pin, slot, or tab, which prevents interchange of otherwise similar appearing fuses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] For example, fuse holders for North American class RK fuses have a pin that prevents installation of similar-appearing class H fuses, which have a much lower breaking capacity and a solid blade terminal that lacks the slot of the RK type.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses can be built with different sized enclosures to prevent interchange of different ratings of fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] For example, *bottle style* fuses distinguish between ratings with different cap diameters.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Automotive glass fuses were made in different lengths, to prevent high-rated fuses being installed in a circuit intended for a lower rating.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Glass cartridge and plug fuses allow direct inspection of the fusible element.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some fuses allow a special purpose micro switch or relay unit to be fixed to the fuse body.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] When the fuse element blows, the indicating pin extends to activate the micro switch or relay, which, in turn, triggers an event.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some fuses for medium-voltage applications use two or three separate barrels and two or three fuse elements in parallel.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The International Electrotechnical Commission publishes standard 60269 for low-voltage power fuses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The standard is in four volumes, which describe general requirements, fuses for industrial and commercial applications, fuses for residential applications, and fuses to protect semiconductor devices.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The IEC standard unifies several national standards, thereby improving the interchangeability of fuses in international trade.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] All fuses of different technologies tested to meet IEC standards will have similar time-current characteristics, which simplifies design and maintenance.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In the United States and Canada, low-voltage fuses to 1 kV AC rating are made in accordance with Underwriters Laboratories standard UL 248 or the harmonized Canadian Standards Association standard C22.2 No.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This standard applies to fuses rated 1 kV or less, AC or DC, and with breaking capacity up to 200 kA.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] These fuses are intended for installations following Canadian Electrical Code, Part I (CEC), or the National Electrical Code, NFPA 70 (NEC).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Additional standard ampere ratings for fuses are 1, 3, 6, 10, and 601.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] UL 248-1 sets the general requirements for fuses, while the latter parts are dedicated to specific fuses sizes (ex: 248-8 for Class J, 248-10 for Class L), or for categories of fuses with unique properties (ex: 248-13 for semiconductor fuses, 248-19 for photovoltaic fuses).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The general requirements (248–1) apply except as modified by the supplemental part (240-x).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] For example, UL 248-19 allows photovoltaic fuses to be rated up to 1500 volts, DC, versus 1000 volts under the general requirements.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] IEC and UL nomenclature varies slightly.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] IEC standards refer to a "fuse" as the assembly of a fusible link and a fuse holder.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In North American standards, the *fuse* is the replaceable portion of the assembly, and a *fuse link* would be a bare metal element for installation in a fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Most automotive fuses rated at 32 volts are used on circuits rated 24 volts DC and below.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some vehicles use a dual 12/42 V DC electrical system that will require a fuse rated at 58 V DC.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses are used on power systems up to 115,000 volts AC.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] High-voltage fuses are used to protect instrument transformers used for electricity metering, or for small power transformers where the expense of a circuit breaker is not warranted.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A circuit breaker at 115 kV may cost up to five times as much as a set of power fuses, so the resulting saving can be tens of thousands of dollars.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In medium-voltage distribution systems, a power fuse may be used to protect a transformer serving 1–3 houses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Pole-mounted distribution transformers are nearly always protected by a fusible cutout, which can have the fuse element replaced using live-line maintenance tools.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Medium-voltage fuses are also used to protect motors, capacitor banks and transformers and may be mounted in metal enclosed switchgear, or (rarely in new designs) on open switchboards.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Large power fuses use fusible elements made of silver, copper or tin to provide stable and predictable performance.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] High voltage *expulsion fuses* surround the fusible link with gas-evolving substances, such as boric acid.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] When the fuse blows, heat from the arc causes the boric acid to evolve large volumes of gases.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The associated high pressure (often greater than 100 atmospheres) and cooling gases rapidly quench the resulting arc.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The hot gases are then explosively expelled out of the end(s) of the fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] These type of fuses may have an impact pin to operate a switch mechanism, so that all three phases are interrupted if any one fuse blows.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses have the advantages of often being less costly and simpler than a circuit breaker for similar ratings.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The blown fuse must be replaced with a new device which is less convenient than simply resetting a breaker and therefore likely to discourage people from ignoring faults.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] On the other hand, replacing a fuse without isolating the circuit first (most building wiring designs do not provide individual isolation switches for each fuse) can be dangerous in itself, particularly if the fault is a short circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In terms of protection response time, fuses tend to isolate faults more quickly (depending on their operating time) than circuit breakers.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A fuse can clear a fault within a quarter cycle of the fault current, while a circuit breaker may take around half to one cycle to clear the fault.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The response time of a fuse can be as fast as 0.002 seconds, whereas a circuit breaker typically responds in the range of 0.02 to 0.05 seconds.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] High rupturing capacity fuses can be rated to safely interrupt up to 300,000 amperes at 600 V AC.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Special current-limiting fuses are applied ahead of some molded-case breakers to protect the breakers in low-voltage power circuits with high short-circuit levels.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some types of circuit breakers must be maintained on a regular basis to ensure their mechanical operation during an interruption.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This is not the case with fuses, which rely on melting processes where no mechanical operation is required for the fuse to operate under fault conditions.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In a multi-phase power circuit, if only one fuse opens, the remaining phases will have higher than normal currents, and unbalanced voltages, with possible damage to motors.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses only sense overcurrent, or to a degree, over-temperature, and cannot usually be used independently with protective relaying to provide more advanced protective functions, for example, ground fault detection.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some manufacturers of medium-voltage distribution fuses combine the overcurrent protection characteristics of the fusible element with the flexibility of relay protection by adding a pyrotechnic device to the fuse operated by external protective relays.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] For domestic applications, Miniature circuit breakers (MCB) are widely used as an alternative to fuses.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Their rated current depend on the load current of the equipment to be protected and the ambient operational temperature.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In the UK, older electrical consumer units (also called fuse boxes) are fitted either with semi-enclosed (rewirable) fuses (BS 3036) or cartridge fuses (BS 1361).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] One form of fuse box abuse was to put a penny in the socket, which defeated overcurrent protection and resulted in a dangerous condition.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Such tampering will not be visible without full inspection of the fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuse wire was never used in North America for this reason, although renewable fuses continue to be made for distribution boards.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The *Wylex standard* consumer unit was very popular in the United Kingdom until the wiring regulations started demanding residual-current devices (RCDs) for sockets that could feasibly supply equipment outside the equipotential zone.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The design does not allow for fitting of RCDs or RCBOs.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some Wylex standard models were made with an RCD instead of the main switch, but (for consumer units supplying the entire installation) this is no longer compliant with the wiring regulations as alarm systems should *not* be RCD-protected.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] There are two styles of fuse base that can be screwed into these units: one designed for rewirable fusewire carriers and one designed for cartridge fuse carriers.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Over the years MCBs have been made for both styles of base.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In both cases, higher rated carriers had wider pins, so a carrier couldn't be changed for a higher rated one without also changing the base.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Cartridge fuse carriers are also now available for DIN-rail enclosures.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In North America, fuses were used in buildings wired before 1960.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] These *Edison base* fuses would screw into a fuse socket similar to Edison-base incandescent lamps.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] To prevent installation of fuses with an excessive current rating, later fuse boxes included rejection features in the fuse-holder socket, commonly known as *Rejection Base (Type S fuses)* which have smaller diameters that vary depending on the rating of the fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This means that fuses can only be replaced by the preset (Type S) fuse rating.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This is a North American, tri-national standard (UL 4248–11; CAN/CSA-C22.2 NO.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Existing Edison fuse boards can easily be converted to only accept Rejection Base (Type S) fuses, by screwing-in a tamper-proof adapter.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This adapter screws into the existing Edison fuse holder, and has a smaller diameter threaded hole to accept the designated Type S rated fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some companies manufacture resettable miniature thermal circuit breakers, which screw into a fuse socket.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Some installations use these Edison-base circuit breakers.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] However, any such breaker sold today does have one flaw.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] It may be installed in a circuit-breaker box with a door.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] If so, if the door is closed, the door may hold down the breaker's reset button.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] While in this state, the breaker is effectively useless: it does not provide any overcurrent protection.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In the 1950s, fuses in new residential or industrial construction for branch circuit protection were superseded by low voltage circuit breakers.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses are widely used for protection of electric motor circuits; for small overloads, the motor protection circuit will open the controlling contactor automatically, and the fuse will only operate for short circuits or extreme overload.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Where several fuses are connected in series at the various levels of a power distribution system, it is desirable to blow (clear) only the fuse (or other overcurrent device) electrically closest to the fault.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] This process is called "coordination" and may require the time-current characteristics of two fuses to be plotted on a common current basis.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Fuses are selected so that the minor branch fuse disconnects its circuit well before the supplying, feeder fuse starts to melt.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] In this way, only the faulty circuit is interrupted with minimal disturbance to other circuits fed by a common supplying fuse.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Where the fuses in a system are of similar types, simple rule-of-thumb ratios between ratings of the fuse closest to the load and the next fuse towards the source can be used.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] So-called self-resetting fuses use a thermoplastic conductive element known as a polymeric positive temperature coefficient (PPTC) thermistor that impedes the circuit during an overcurrent condition (by increasing device resistance).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The PPTC thermistor is self-resetting in that when current is removed, the device will cool and revert to low resistance.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] These devices are often used in aerospace/nuclear applications where replacement is difficult, or on a computer motherboard so that a shorted mouse or keyboard does not cause motherboard damage.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A *thermal fuse* is often found in consumer equipment such as coffee makers, hair dryers or transformers powering small consumer electronics devices.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] They contain a fusible, temperature-sensitive composition which holds a spring contact mechanism normally closed.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] When the surrounding temperature gets too high, the composition melts and allows the spring contact mechanism to break the circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The device can be used to prevent a fire in a hair dryer for example, by cutting off the power supply to the heater elements when the air flow is interrupted (e.g., the blower motor stops or the air intake becomes accidentally blocked).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] Thermal fuses are a 'one shot', non-resettable device which must be replaced once they have been activated (blown).
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] A cable limiter is similar to a fuse but is intended only for protection of low voltage power cables.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] It is used, for example, in networks where multiple cables may be used in parallel.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] It is not intended to provide overload protection, but instead protects a cable that is exposed to a short circuit.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The characteristics of the limiter are matched to the size of cable so that the limiter clears a fault before the cable insulation is damaged.
[src:fuse-electrical/fuse-electrical] The Unicode character for the fuse's schematic symbol, found in the Miscellaneous Technical block, is U+23DB (⏛).
